WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
[Unknown]: IVM

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:03.640
[Amit Varma]: Let me elaborate. When you go out for coffee or dinner with friends,

00:01:03.640 --> 00:01:07.560
[Amit Varma]: do you force them to eat whatever you're having or what you feel is good for them?

00:01:07.720 --> 00:01:14.040
[Amit Varma]: No, you don't. You respect the individual autonomy and you expect them to respect yours, as they usually do.

00:01:14.140 --> 00:01:17.960
[Amit Varma]: At the end when the bill comes, you might insist on paying for it yourself,

00:01:18.220 --> 00:01:20.640
[Amit Varma]: but you never insist that one of them pays for it.

00:01:20.640 --> 00:01:25.480
[Amit Varma]: You don't steal money from their wallet when they are not looking and you don't try to leave the restaurant without paying.

00:01:25.480 --> 00:01:27.820
[Amit Varma]: And if you see a beggar outside and feel sorry for him,

00:01:27.820 --> 00:01:30.560
[Amit Varma]: you may leave the beggar something of your own volition,

00:01:30.560 --> 00:01:35.200
[Amit Varma]: but you would think it outrageous to pay nothing yourself, but force your friends to pay.

00:01:35.280 --> 00:01:36.840
[Amit Varma]: You see what I'm getting at here, right?

00:01:36.840 --> 00:01:40.940
[Amit Varma]: We all respect the autonomy of others and we all respect the choices they make.

00:01:41.400 --> 00:01:47.360
[Amit Varma]: Consent is a big deal for us and we don't try to force other adults to do things against their wish.

00:01:47.600 --> 00:01:54.000
[Amit Varma]: We agree that violence is bad, except in self-defense. We believe in the dignity of the individual.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:58.000
[Unknown]: We are all libertarians.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:36.480
[Amit Varma]: We have no objection to state violence or to the state doing things to us that we would be outraged if anyone else did.

00:02:36.480 --> 00:02:42.720
[Amit Varma]: We misunderstand how society works and believe that societies and economies can be planned and engineered

00:02:42.720 --> 00:02:48.320
[Amit Varma]: and ignore the fact that such planning on the behalf of others always involves violence.

00:02:48.320 --> 00:02:53.920
[Amit Varma]: Indeed, the everyday violence we face has been normalized so much that we don't think of it as violence at all.

00:02:53.920 --> 00:03:01.520
[Amit Varma]: Now, it's what I call the liberal paradox that we need the state to protect our rights and its existence does imply a certain amount of violence.

00:03:01.520 --> 00:03:06.560
[Amit Varma]: But the modern state, everywhere in the world and especially in India, goes far beyond this.

00:03:06.560 --> 00:03:09.520
[Amit Varma]: And this is a battle that libertarians constantly fight.

00:03:09.520 --> 00:03:15.520
[Amit Varma]: This normalization of violence, this overriding of individual rights in the name of an illusory greater good,

00:03:15.520 --> 00:03:18.000
[Amit Varma]: the daily assaults on human dignity.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:20.160
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is a man I admire deeply.

00:03:20.160 --> 00:03:26.480
[Amit Varma]: David Boaz wrote the book that first introduced me to the ideas of libertarianism, which I read at the turn of the millennium.

00:03:26.480 --> 00:03:35.120
[Amit Varma]: That book was called Libertarianism, a Primer, which he updated and expanded a few years ago into a fantastic book called The Libertarian Mind.

00:03:35.120 --> 00:03:42.240
[Amit Varma]: He writes prolifically about libertarianism and works now as an executive vice president at the Cato Institute in Washington, D.C.

00:03:42.240 --> 00:03:48.240
[Amit Varma]: He has also been the editor of the Libertarian Reader, an excellent collection of writings about liberalism through the ages,

00:03:48.240 --> 00:03:54.480
[Amit Varma]: and the co-editor of the Cato Handbook for Congress and the Cato Handbook on Policy, which are brilliant guides to good governance.

00:03:54.480 --> 00:03:58.320
[Amit Varma]: He was kind enough to give me two hours of his time and we chatted over Skype.

