00:05:05.280 --> 00:05:12.480
[Amit Varma]: David, before we start off, tell me a little bit about you and about how you came to libertarian ideas.

00:05:12.480 --> 00:05:17.440
[Amit Varma]: Because when you were kind of growing up in the States, libertarian ideas weren't so common back then, right?

00:05:18.960 --> 00:05:20.400
[Guest]: Well, that's right.

00:05:20.400 --> 00:05:31.760
[Guest]: On the other hand, basic libertarian ideas about individual freedom and self-reliance and not trusting the government are pretty basic to America.

00:05:31.760 --> 00:05:36.160
[Guest]: So in that sense, there was a decent background there.

00:05:36.160 --> 00:05:40.480
[Guest]: I grew up in Kentucky, in the middle of the country, sort of the South.

00:05:41.040 --> 00:05:44.560
[Guest]: And my parents were well-educated.

00:05:44.560 --> 00:05:47.520
[Guest]: I always say I'm the first in my family not to be a lawyer.

00:05:49.120 --> 00:05:52.640
[Guest]: So there was political conversation in my house.

00:05:53.280 --> 00:05:56.240
[Guest]: Not sure my brother and sister paid that much attention to it.

00:05:56.240 --> 00:06:02.080
[Guest]: But I talked about politics and policy somewhat with my parents.

00:06:02.080 --> 00:06:10.400
[Guest]: And then when I was in high school, I read Barry Goldwater's Conscience of a Conservative,

00:06:10.400 --> 00:06:16.880
[Guest]: which is actually a very libertarian book because much of American conservatism is very libertarian.

00:06:16.880 --> 00:06:20.400
[Guest]: And then I read Economics in One Lesson by Henry Hazlitt.

00:06:20.400 --> 00:06:22.560
[Guest]: And then I read Ayn Rand.

00:06:22.560 --> 00:06:27.040
[Guest]: And by that point, I was pretty much on the way to being a committed libertarian.

00:06:27.600 --> 00:06:38.000
[Guest]: And yes, finding actual libertarianism there around 1970, early 70s, was pretty hard.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:39.120
[Unknown]: It was a small movement.

00:06:39.120 --> 00:06:40.560
[Guest]: And of course, we had no internet.

00:06:40.560 --> 00:06:41.760
[Guest]: So it was harder to find.

00:06:42.560 --> 00:06:46.800
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, back then, there was no Cato, no Students for Liberty, no Reason magazine.

00:06:46.800 --> 00:06:49.600
[Amit Varma]: How do you sort of find other people who think like you?

00:06:49.600 --> 00:06:53.840
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, are there moments of sort of self-doubt when where you wonder,

00:06:53.840 --> 00:06:55.040
[Amit Varma]: is there something wrong with me?

00:06:55.040 --> 00:06:57.520
[Amit Varma]: Because I'm the only one who looks at the world like this.

00:06:58.640 --> 00:07:01.120
[Guest]: Well, I don't know that I ever felt quite like that.

00:07:01.120 --> 00:07:08.160
[Guest]: Like I say, there are basic libertarian ideas that suffuse American thought.

00:07:09.200 --> 00:07:15.040
[Guest]: Ayn Rand was a best-selling author, and it wasn't hard as a high school student to discover

00:07:15.040 --> 00:07:16.160
[Guest]: Ayn Rand's work.

00:07:16.160 --> 00:07:21.280
[Guest]: I sort of stumbled on Henry Hazlitt, but Barry Goldwater had run for president on

00:07:22.160 --> 00:07:25.440
[Guest]: a very conservative, but in some ways libertarian platform.

00:07:25.440 --> 00:07:27.120
[Guest]: So people knew about that.

00:07:27.120 --> 00:07:33.120
[Guest]: And what happened was that when I got to college, I joined a conservative group,

00:07:33.120 --> 00:07:34.640
[Guest]: Young Americans for Freedom.

00:07:34.640 --> 00:07:36.960
[Guest]: And of course, they said they were for freedom.

00:07:36.960 --> 00:07:40.240
[Guest]: And we were for free markets and free enterprise.

00:07:40.240 --> 00:07:47.200
[Guest]: And I came to discover partly by reading their magazine, oh, I see these tensions in conservatism.

00:07:47.200 --> 00:07:48.560
[Guest]: Sometimes they're for freedom.

00:07:48.560 --> 00:07:52.400
[Guest]: Sometimes they're talking about imposed order.

00:07:52.400 --> 00:07:54.720
[Guest]: And it's the freedom part that I like.

00:07:56.400 --> 00:08:01.280
[Guest]: Once you got hold of a copy of Reason magazine, then you would see ads for other libertarian

00:08:01.280 --> 00:08:02.400
[Guest]: projects.

00:08:02.400 --> 00:08:05.680
[Guest]: So I met people in college and then after college.

00:08:05.680 --> 00:08:07.280
[Guest]: It was actually an exciting time.

00:08:07.280 --> 00:08:12.000
[Guest]: For libertarians, I should also mention there was the Foundation for Economic Education,

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:12.560
[Guest]: FEE.

00:08:12.560 --> 00:08:17.680
[Guest]: And a lot of young conservatives got FEE's magazine, The Freeman.

00:08:17.680 --> 00:08:24.240
[Guest]: And that was a way to get connected to a network of people who did believe in freedom.

00:08:25.520 --> 00:08:31.600
[Guest]: But the mid 1970s was a pretty exciting time because you did have the Libertarian Party

00:08:31.600 --> 00:08:33.120
[Guest]: being founded.

00:08:33.120 --> 00:08:34.240
[Guest]: You had Hayek.

00:08:34.240 --> 00:08:37.360
[Guest]: And Friedman winning Nobel Prizes.

00:08:37.360 --> 00:08:40.560
[Guest]: You had Robert Nozick's book coming out and winning a National Book Award.

00:08:41.440 --> 00:08:45.920
[Guest]: A little bit after that, then you did have the creation of the Cato Institute.

00:08:45.920 --> 00:08:49.440
[Guest]: And of course, Reason magazine, I think, goes back to 1969.

00:08:49.440 --> 00:08:54.560
[Guest]: So it was a smaller and less professional looking magazine then.

00:08:54.560 --> 00:08:56.720
[Guest]: But it was an exciting time.

00:08:56.720 --> 00:08:58.320
[Guest]: It was the beginning of a movement.

00:08:58.960 --> 00:09:03.040
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, just looking back at when I grew up in New York, I was a little bit more

00:09:03.040 --> 00:09:07.360
[Amit Varma]: conservative, but looking back at when I grew up in India, which was somewhat later than

00:09:07.360 --> 00:09:12.880
[Amit Varma]: you, and we obviously didn't have these fundamental American values of individual freedom and

00:09:12.880 --> 00:09:16.480
[Amit Varma]: so on, which, you know, is embedded in your constitution and your way of thinking.

00:09:16.480 --> 00:09:20.240
[Amit Varma]: Over here, I often say that India's biggest religion is a religion of government.

00:09:20.240 --> 00:09:23.360
[Amit Varma]: I mean, statism is just sort of reflexive.

00:09:23.360 --> 00:09:25.920
[Amit Varma]: State violence is completely normalized.

00:09:25.920 --> 00:09:30.000
[Amit Varma]: And so it was very refreshing for me almost a couple of decades ago to read your book

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:33.760
[Amit Varma]: later, updated to the libertarian mind, which came out a few years ago.

00:09:33.760 --> 00:09:38.240
[Amit Varma]: Now, what I found interesting about the libertarian mind was at the start of it, you write about

00:09:38.240 --> 00:09:41.360
[Amit Varma]: how the world is becoming more libertarian.

00:09:41.360 --> 00:09:46.880
[Amit Varma]: And if you look at the broader arc of history, that certainly seems to be true to some extent

00:09:46.880 --> 00:09:48.000
[Amit Varma]: at that time.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:53.040
[Amit Varma]: But now, now that we live in the age of Trump and, you know, in India, Modi, for example,

00:09:53.040 --> 00:09:58.720
[Amit Varma]: authoritarian populace across the world coming to power, and the discourse everywhere being

00:09:58.720 --> 00:10:04.640
[Amit Varma]: arguments between different kinds of statism and not for liberty at all.

00:10:04.640 --> 00:10:05.920
[Amit Varma]: Are you still as optimistic?

00:10:07.760 --> 00:10:10.640
[Guest]: Well, maybe not as optimistic, but I actually would sort of.

00:10:12.720 --> 00:10:14.400
[Guest]: Let's look at three things there.

00:10:14.400 --> 00:10:17.520
[Guest]: One is, is the world getting better?

00:10:17.520 --> 00:10:18.800
[Guest]: Yes, absolutely.

00:10:19.440 --> 00:10:23.440
[Guest]: The world is getting more prosperous and the prosperity is more widespread.

00:10:23.440 --> 00:10:31.680
[Guest]: And the opportunity for people to pursue happiness in their own way is more broadly available

00:10:31.680 --> 00:10:33.920
[Guest]: in more countries in the world.

00:10:33.920 --> 00:10:40.320
[Guest]: And of course, the good changes in China and India over the past generation account for

00:10:40.320 --> 00:10:46.640
[Guest]: a lot of that progress and optimism because there are so many people to whom those changes

00:10:46.640 --> 00:10:47.680
[Guest]: are relevant.

00:10:47.680 --> 00:10:54.800
[Guest]: So our website, humanprogress.org, details continuing progress on hunger, illiteracy,

00:10:54.800 --> 00:10:56.400
[Guest]: poverty, and so on.

00:10:57.280 --> 00:11:03.440
[Guest]: Is the world getting freer, which is somewhat different, though usually connected?

00:11:03.440 --> 00:11:05.280
[Guest]: Yes, I think it still is.

00:11:05.280 --> 00:11:12.800
[Guest]: I think that the economic reforms in India and I think in China and I think in India,

00:11:12.800 --> 00:11:18.320
[Guest]: though I certainly yield to your expertise on that, but also some economic reforms even

00:11:18.320 --> 00:11:26.640
[Guest]: happening in Africa, the decline of military dictatorships in Latin America, some policy

00:11:26.640 --> 00:11:31.200
[Guest]: reforms in developed countries.

00:11:31.200 --> 00:11:35.520
[Guest]: Yes, I think overall we still are seeing more freedom.

00:11:35.520 --> 00:11:38.720
[Guest]: Now, what about our politics?

00:11:38.720 --> 00:11:44.800
[Guest]: Well, yes, politics seems to have taken a turn for the worse since I was writing The

00:11:44.800 --> 00:11:47.280
[Guest]: Libertarian Mind around 2013.

00:11:48.080 --> 00:11:52.720
[Guest]: We do have the rise of authoritarians in a lot of places.

00:11:52.720 --> 00:11:58.320
[Guest]: I've been saying in speeches lately, ideas we thought were dead are back.

00:11:58.320 --> 00:12:06.320
[Guest]: Ideas like socialism, economic nationalism, authoritarianism, even fascism.

00:12:06.320 --> 00:12:14.240
[Guest]: And we're facing fundamental challenges to liberalism in a way that in 2013 I probably

00:12:14.240 --> 00:12:17.040
[Guest]: didn't sense was the case.

00:12:17.040 --> 00:12:23.040
[Guest]: So intellectually and politically, we have big challenges right now, probably more so

00:12:23.040 --> 00:12:25.440
[Guest]: than I thought in 2013.

00:12:25.440 --> 00:12:32.080
[Guest]: But so far, I think we are still on a path of greater freedom.

00:12:32.080 --> 00:12:37.200
[Guest]: But if the politics continues in the direction it's been going the last few years, then that

00:12:37.200 --> 00:12:38.240
[Guest]: will change.

00:12:38.240 --> 00:12:42.880
[Guest]: And it's interesting that the dead ideas that have been revived that you named like

00:12:42.880 --> 00:12:47.280
[Amit Varma]: socialism, economic nationalism, fascism, they're all isms.

00:12:47.280 --> 00:12:51.440
[Amit Varma]: And that's kind of the reason I sometimes feel uncomfortable with the world, with the

00:12:51.440 --> 00:12:56.720
[Amit Varma]: word libertarianism, because it seems to imply that it's a system of thinking that depends

00:12:56.720 --> 00:12:59.120
[Amit Varma]: on certain facts about the world.

00:12:59.120 --> 00:13:02.320
[Amit Varma]: But actually, to me, it's just really a value system.

00:13:02.320 --> 00:13:06.640
[Amit Varma]: You respect individual autonomy, the dignity of others, you value consent and you stand

00:13:06.640 --> 00:13:08.080
[Amit Varma]: against coercion.

00:13:08.080 --> 00:13:09.280
[Amit Varma]: Nothing more and nothing less.

00:13:09.280 --> 00:13:13.040
[Amit Varma]: It's not like one of the others in that sense.

00:13:13.040 --> 00:13:17.440
[Amit Varma]: So let's let's kind of talk about the fundamentals of sort of libertarianism.

00:13:17.440 --> 00:13:19.440
[Amit Varma]: What does it mean to you in simple terms?

00:13:20.560 --> 00:13:28.560
[Guest]: What I like to say in speeches is libertarianism is the idea that a democracy is a system of

00:13:28.560 --> 00:13:34.320
[Guest]: thinking that adults, individuals have the right and the responsibility to make the important

00:13:34.320 --> 00:13:36.800
[Guest]: decisions about their own lives.

00:13:36.800 --> 00:13:39.440
[Guest]: And each word is important there.

00:13:39.440 --> 00:13:43.680
[Guest]: This is about the rights of adults, not necessarily children.

00:13:43.680 --> 00:13:45.680
[Guest]: That's a more complicated issue.

00:13:45.680 --> 00:13:53.680
[Guest]: This is also about individuals making decisions, not collectives, not nations to the extent

00:13:53.680 --> 00:13:56.720
[Guest]: that we can avoid that, not racial groups and so on.

00:13:56.720 --> 00:13:58.960
[Guest]: Have the right, because as.

00:14:00.240 --> 00:14:06.480
[Guest]: Individuals as autonomous thinking, rational beings, we have the right to make the important

00:14:06.480 --> 00:14:08.240
[Guest]: decisions about our lives.

00:14:08.240 --> 00:14:14.560
[Guest]: But with those rights go responsibilities, not imposed responsibilities, but just the

00:14:14.560 --> 00:14:21.520
[Guest]: idea that if I make choices, I bear the consequences for the outcome of those choices.

00:14:21.520 --> 00:14:23.440
[Guest]: And that's a responsibility.

00:14:23.440 --> 00:14:27.440
[Guest]: And when we start thinking about sometimes people listen to that and they say, well,

00:14:27.440 --> 00:14:28.960
[Guest]: yes, but we do have that.

00:14:28.960 --> 00:14:30.400
[Guest]: But what's your complaint?

00:14:30.400 --> 00:14:36.480
[Guest]: Well, of course, my complaint is that the government takes half the income I earn and

00:14:36.480 --> 00:14:41.120
[Guest]: it tells me how I have to save for retirement and how I have to give to charity.

00:14:41.120 --> 00:14:45.840
[Guest]: It tells me what I can smoke and what I can drink and what I can read and who I can marry.

00:14:45.840 --> 00:14:49.280
[Guest]: And obviously not all of those things in any country at any one time.

00:14:49.280 --> 00:14:55.920
[Guest]: But but those kinds of things are the decisions that government is arrogating to itself to

00:14:55.920 --> 00:14:57.920
[Guest]: make those decisions for me.

00:14:58.560 --> 00:15:01.120
[Guest]: I want the right to make those decisions.

00:15:01.120 --> 00:15:03.440
[Guest]: But that does mean that there will be consequences.

00:15:03.440 --> 00:15:08.480
[Guest]: And so I have a responsibility if I become a drunk or a drug addict.

00:15:09.280 --> 00:15:10.160
[Guest]: That's on me.

00:15:10.160 --> 00:15:17.360
[Guest]: Mostly if I don't save for my retirement, then I have to assume I have to accept responsibility

00:15:17.360 --> 00:15:18.320
[Guest]: for that.

00:15:18.320 --> 00:15:22.800
[Guest]: I think parents should have the right to decide where their children will be educated and

00:15:22.800 --> 00:15:23.520
[Guest]: how.

00:15:23.520 --> 00:15:27.040
[Guest]: That's also a responsibility as a parent.

00:15:27.040 --> 00:15:32.240
[Guest]: You should want to make the important decisions about guiding your child's life.

00:15:32.240 --> 00:15:37.360
[Guest]: And you you bear the consequences of those decisions.

00:15:37.360 --> 00:15:38.560
[Guest]: And of course, so do your children.

00:15:38.560 --> 00:15:41.920
[Guest]: And that's why it's so important to get them right.

00:15:41.920 --> 00:15:51.920
[Guest]: So in all of those areas, government is impinging, intruding on our right and responsibility to

00:15:51.920 --> 00:15:54.080
[Guest]: be fully responsible adults.

00:15:54.720 --> 00:15:58.000
[Amit Varma]: In fact, there's a really nice quote from your book, which I'm going to read out.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:01.200
[Amit Varma]: Quote, Libertarians believe in the presumption of liberty.

00:16:01.200 --> 00:16:05.600
[Amit Varma]: That is, Libertarians believe that people ought to be free to live as they choose, unless

00:16:05.600 --> 00:16:08.240
[Amit Varma]: advocates of coercion can make a compelling case.

00:16:08.240 --> 00:16:13.200
[Amit Varma]: It's the exercise of power, not the exercise of freedom that requires justification.

00:16:13.200 --> 00:16:14.000
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:18.800
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, this is a very profound sentence, because what has happened in our world today,

00:16:18.800 --> 00:16:23.840
[Amit Varma]: especially in India, but I think everywhere is a normalization of coercion, where we take

00:16:23.840 --> 00:16:29.120
[Amit Varma]: a lot of state violence and state interference in our lives completely for granted.

00:16:29.120 --> 00:16:32.320
[Amit Varma]: You know, sometimes when I tell people that taxes are a form of coercion, it's a form

00:16:32.320 --> 00:16:32.880
[Amit Varma]: of violence.

00:16:32.880 --> 00:16:36.480
[Amit Varma]: And they're like, they look at me aghast as if, you know, what on earth am I talking

00:16:36.480 --> 00:16:36.720
[Amit Varma]: about?

00:16:36.720 --> 00:16:39.440
[Amit Varma]: It's been so normalized.

00:16:39.440 --> 00:16:42.720
[Amit Varma]: And another sentence from your book, which I often, in fact, use at the start of slide

00:16:42.720 --> 00:16:47.280
[Amit Varma]: shows when I talk about libertarianism is, quote, in a sense that have always been but

00:16:47.280 --> 00:16:50.800
[Amit Varma]: two political philosophies, liberty and power.

00:16:50.800 --> 00:16:51.680
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:16:51.680 --> 00:16:56.560
[Amit Varma]: And the arc of history really seems to be coming from a point where power is dominant

00:16:56.560 --> 00:16:59.680
[Amit Varma]: to a point where liberty is asserting itself more and more.

00:17:00.960 --> 00:17:01.920
[Guest]: Well, that's right.

00:17:01.920 --> 00:17:08.240
[Guest]: And so all of these things are problems right now, but they have been problems in the past.

00:17:08.240 --> 00:17:16.960
[Guest]: And in most societies, they were more severe problems in the past, especially if we go

00:17:16.960 --> 00:17:21.280
[Guest]: back before the rise of liberalism in the 17th and 18th centuries.

00:17:21.840 --> 00:17:25.520
[Guest]: For obviously, I know the history of the West better.

00:17:25.520 --> 00:17:31.200
[Guest]: The combination of church and state, the assumption that everything will stay the same, that

00:17:31.200 --> 00:17:38.000
[Guest]: people's places in society are fixed, that if you're born a serf, your children will

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:39.440
[Guest]: be born serfs as well.

00:17:40.080 --> 00:17:45.120
[Guest]: All of that was a massive system of organized coercion.

00:17:45.120 --> 00:17:50.720
[Guest]: And of course, if you go back before that, we can argue that the the origin of states

00:17:50.720 --> 00:17:57.120
[Guest]: was that the strong picked up sticks and threatened to hit or kill the weak.

00:17:57.120 --> 00:18:01.360
[Guest]: And that's how some people achieve power over others.

00:18:01.360 --> 00:18:06.560
[Guest]: But when liberalism came into the world, that was the problem.

00:18:06.560 --> 00:18:12.880
[Guest]: They were concerned about the denial of individual responsibility, of individual thought, freedom

00:18:12.880 --> 00:18:21.360
[Guest]: of speech, freedom of religion and the use of power to impose other people's will on

00:18:21.360 --> 00:18:22.080
[Guest]: you.

00:18:22.080 --> 00:18:29.040
[Guest]: And so since liberalism came into the world, in increasing parts of the world, people do

00:18:29.040 --> 00:18:33.280
[Guest]: stand up and say that kind of coercion is not right.

00:18:33.280 --> 00:18:41.120
[Guest]: Now, you're correct to say that so many kinds of coercion go unchallenged, unnoticed by

00:18:41.120 --> 00:18:41.920
[Guest]: most people.

00:18:41.920 --> 00:18:43.840
[Guest]: And there are different reasons for that.

00:18:43.840 --> 00:18:50.000
[Guest]: And many people believe that it's just necessary for the state to do more things than I think

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:52.160
[Guest]: it's necessary for the state to do.

00:18:52.160 --> 00:18:56.400
[Guest]: But there are also many people who have a personal agenda.

00:18:56.400 --> 00:19:00.320
[Guest]: They want their religious views imposed on everyone.

00:19:00.320 --> 00:19:02.720
[Guest]: They want their political views imposed.

00:19:03.280 --> 00:19:09.520
[Guest]: They want the state to take wealth from other people and give it to them or to prevent other

00:19:09.520 --> 00:19:16.240
[Guest]: people from competing with them and possibly challenging their economic security.

00:19:16.240 --> 00:19:25.360
[Guest]: So there are many reasons that we haven't fully accepted the principle of liberty.

00:19:25.360 --> 00:19:31.680
[Guest]: But the principle of liberty, principle of natural rights, of human rights for the past

00:19:32.240 --> 00:19:38.640
[Guest]: two or three centuries has been there as a vision and a beacon that can inspire people

00:19:38.640 --> 00:19:42.400
[Guest]: and encourage them to push back against power.

00:19:42.400 --> 00:19:45.600
[Guest]: What were the American revolutionaries concerned about?

00:19:45.600 --> 00:19:50.320
[Guest]: They were concerned about the way Britain was exercising power in this country.

00:19:50.320 --> 00:19:56.880
[Guest]: But they were also concerned from their study of history about the general problem of power,

00:19:56.880 --> 00:20:01.280
[Guest]: that people with power will always want to extend it.

00:20:02.880 --> 00:20:03.120
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:20:03.120 --> 00:20:06.480
[Amit Varma]: And I should clarify for my listeners that, you know, I'm saying libertarianism, you're

00:20:06.480 --> 00:20:07.200
[Amit Varma]: saying liberalism.

00:20:07.200 --> 00:20:08.880
[Amit Varma]: We basically mean the same thing.

00:20:08.880 --> 00:20:12.880
[Amit Varma]: It, you know, this started off as liberalism, you know, a belief in human liberty.

00:20:12.880 --> 00:20:17.760
[Amit Varma]: And then the term liberalism somehow morphed towards the start of the 20th century, as

00:20:17.760 --> 00:20:18.960
[Amit Varma]: you describe in your book.

00:20:18.960 --> 00:20:21.600
[Amit Varma]: And now it means different things in different parts of the world.

00:20:21.600 --> 00:20:26.720
[Amit Varma]: So especially in America, where, you know, it means almost the opposite of what it used

00:20:26.720 --> 00:20:27.200
[Amit Varma]: to.

00:20:27.200 --> 00:20:31.440
[Amit Varma]: And old school liberals like us are called classical liberals by some, libertarians

00:20:31.440 --> 00:20:32.320
[Amit Varma]: by others.

00:20:32.320 --> 00:20:34.640
[Amit Varma]: It's all really fundamentally the same thing.

00:20:34.640 --> 00:20:35.360
[Amit Varma]: It's really simple.

00:20:35.360 --> 00:20:39.600
[Amit Varma]: It goes down to the principle of like, you know, as you say in your book, the essence

00:20:39.600 --> 00:20:42.080
[Amit Varma]: of this is something you learn in kindergarten.

00:20:42.080 --> 00:20:45.680
[Amit Varma]: Don't hit other people, don't take their stuff and keep your promises.

00:20:46.560 --> 00:20:52.160
[Amit Varma]: Just sort of talking about how sort of liberty began to assert itself against power, as it

00:20:52.160 --> 00:20:54.880
[Amit Varma]: were, in this sort of long battle.

00:20:54.880 --> 00:20:58.400
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, the key point is the enlightenment.

00:20:58.400 --> 00:21:04.000
[Amit Varma]: So take me through a little bit of the early history of liberalism slash libertarianism

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:07.280
[Amit Varma]: and why John Locke is so important there.

00:21:07.280 --> 00:21:09.120
[Amit Varma]: And what are the ideas that came out of that?

00:21:10.960 --> 00:21:20.160
[Guest]: Like I say, in the Western world, there was for 1500 years or so a dominant Catholic church.

00:21:20.160 --> 00:21:29.840
[Guest]: There were also princes and kings around Europe, and both parties had an interest in essentially

00:21:29.840 --> 00:21:31.120
[Guest]: keeping things the same.

00:21:31.120 --> 00:21:35.840
[Guest]: The kings want to know that their sons and grandsons will also be kings.

00:21:35.840 --> 00:21:41.120
[Guest]: And that necessarily implies that the sons and grandsons of the serfs and the peasants

00:21:41.120 --> 00:21:43.120
[Guest]: will remain in their state.

00:21:43.920 --> 00:21:52.880
[Guest]: And the church at that time was not very open to scientific thinking that might challenge

00:21:52.880 --> 00:22:04.240
[Guest]: the central role of religion in the world. Sometime around 1500, really, people started

00:22:04.240 --> 00:22:06.160
[Guest]: thinking scientifically.

00:22:06.160 --> 00:22:10.640
[Guest]: They started using their reason to try to understand the world.

00:22:10.640 --> 00:22:18.960
[Guest]: And you get people like Galileo and Vesalius and Copernicus and Newton taking a genuinely

00:22:18.960 --> 00:22:26.640
[Guest]: new scientific approach to understanding how our bodies work, how nature works, how the

00:22:26.640 --> 00:22:30.960
[Guest]: heavens work, how the bodies in the universe work.

00:22:31.760 --> 00:22:33.760
[Guest]: And this was a new thing.

00:22:33.760 --> 00:22:39.920
[Guest]: This was the application of reason to understanding the world around us.

00:22:39.920 --> 00:22:47.280
[Guest]: And as people started doing that, it led them to some extent to question the rules that

00:22:47.280 --> 00:22:50.080
[Guest]: authorities had set up for the world.

00:22:50.080 --> 00:22:54.640
[Guest]: So, Steven Pinker in his new book, Enlightenment Now, which I think you've talked about on

00:22:54.640 --> 00:23:03.600
[Guest]: here, identifies four elements of the Enlightenment, reason, science, humanism, and progress.

00:23:03.600 --> 00:23:08.320
[Guest]: Reason, the use of the human capacity to understand and analyze.

00:23:08.320 --> 00:23:12.560
[Guest]: Science, the application of reason to the natural world.

00:23:12.560 --> 00:23:18.800
[Guest]: Humanism, the idea that human institutions should be judged by how well they serve humanity.

00:23:19.360 --> 00:23:23.360
[Guest]: And then progress, the idea that things actually can change.

00:23:23.360 --> 00:23:24.640
[Guest]: They can get better.

00:23:24.640 --> 00:23:29.680
[Guest]: We can discover how the body works and use that to save lives.

00:23:29.680 --> 00:23:35.920
[Guest]: We can discover how nature works and harness it to provide us eventually with running water

00:23:35.920 --> 00:23:38.320
[Guest]: and electricity and all those kinds of things.

00:23:38.320 --> 00:23:46.960
[Guest]: And we can come to understand how commerce makes people treat one another better.

00:23:47.920 --> 00:23:52.640
[Guest]: Sort of an old idea, you know, two ways of acquiring wealth.

00:23:52.640 --> 00:23:57.680
[Guest]: You can either take it from people or you can trade something for it.

00:23:57.680 --> 00:24:06.160
[Guest]: And in the Enlightenment liberal era, people started examining the way that trade was done.

00:24:06.160 --> 00:24:15.040
[Guest]: They started examining the way that trading is better in terms of social peace and actual

00:24:15.040 --> 00:24:22.640
[Guest]: economic growth, and also noticed that people who come to each other as traders tend to

00:24:22.640 --> 00:24:24.080
[Guest]: treat each other better.

00:24:24.080 --> 00:24:27.440
[Guest]: I've seen some scholars talk about the double thank you.

00:24:27.440 --> 00:24:31.360
[Guest]: When I buy something, I say thank you to the clerk and he says thank you to me.

00:24:31.360 --> 00:24:35.360
[Guest]: Because in that transaction, we've both been made better off.

00:24:35.360 --> 00:24:38.800
[Guest]: He now has money to buy whatever he needs.

00:24:39.600 --> 00:24:47.520
[Guest]: So this was the Enlightenment, the understanding that we could seek to understand and we could

00:24:47.520 --> 00:24:49.040
[Guest]: anticipate progress.

00:24:49.040 --> 00:24:55.200
[Guest]: And then I think it's in that era that people start thinking about political institutions.

00:24:55.200 --> 00:25:00.560
[Guest]: What is the nature of man and what political institutions would best serve man?

00:25:00.560 --> 00:25:02.960
[Guest]: And that's where John Locke comes in.

00:25:02.960 --> 00:25:06.720
[Guest]: About 1690, publishes his second treatise of government.

00:25:08.400 --> 00:25:11.280
[Guest]: And it says, what is the point of government?

00:25:11.280 --> 00:25:16.160
[Guest]: Governments are created to protect our rights, our rights of life, liberty, and property.

00:25:16.160 --> 00:25:21.200
[Guest]: And we could try to protect them ourselves with sticks or guns or whatever we have.

00:25:21.200 --> 00:25:26.560
[Guest]: But there are certainly some good reasons to prefer that we create an organization that

00:25:26.560 --> 00:25:31.440
[Guest]: will protect all of our rights and hopefully do so in a peaceful way.

00:25:31.440 --> 00:25:37.600
[Guest]: So government is created to protect individual rights and to protect private property.

00:25:37.600 --> 00:25:43.040
[Guest]: And if government is not serving those purposes, as we said in the Declaration of Independence,

00:25:43.040 --> 00:25:46.000
[Guest]: it is the right of the people to alter or abolish it.

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:52.240
[Guest]: And then from John Locke's work on individual rights and the nature of government and Adam

00:25:52.240 --> 00:25:59.040
[Guest]: Smith's work on spontaneous order and economics, we get really the whole flourishing of liberal

00:25:59.040 --> 00:26:05.840
[Guest]: thought, now maybe known as libertarian thought, and also the flourishing of the world from

00:26:05.840 --> 00:26:13.760
[Guest]: a world of backbreaking poverty and short life expectancies up until about 1700 and

00:26:13.760 --> 00:26:21.600
[Guest]: the incredible progress of technology and economics and society since then.

00:26:22.480 --> 00:26:27.280
[Amit Varma]: And the reason this happens, obviously, is that once people have the freedom, so to say,

00:26:27.280 --> 00:26:33.040
[Amit Varma]: to associate with others in whatever way they want, consenting adults can do whatever they

00:26:33.040 --> 00:26:35.680
[Amit Varma]: want with each other, whether in the bedroom or in the marketplace.

00:26:35.680 --> 00:26:39.680
[Amit Varma]: And that leads to a positive some game like you described it, I think it's John Stossel's

00:26:39.680 --> 00:26:44.800
[Amit Varma]: phrase, a double thank you moment, where both parties trading get better off and the amount

00:26:44.800 --> 00:26:50.160
[Amit Varma]: of value in the world grows up, which is really the secret of all human success.

00:26:50.160 --> 00:26:54.480
[Amit Varma]: But sort of going back to Locke, I'll just quote another bit from your book where you

00:26:54.480 --> 00:27:00.000
[Amit Varma]: cite Locke, start quote, people have rights prior to the existence of government.

00:27:00.000 --> 00:27:03.040
[Amit Varma]: Thus, we call them natural rights because they exist in nature.

00:27:03.040 --> 00:27:05.680
[Amit Varma]: People form a government to protect their rights.

00:27:05.680 --> 00:27:09.600
[Amit Varma]: They could do that without government, but a government is an efficient system for protecting

00:27:09.600 --> 00:27:10.000
[Amit Varma]: rights.

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:15.680
[Amit Varma]: And if government exceeds that role, people are justified in revolting.

00:27:15.680 --> 00:27:16.320
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:27:17.040 --> 00:27:20.960
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, just unpack this a little bit for me.

00:27:20.960 --> 00:27:24.800
[Amit Varma]: What what did Locke mean by natural rights per se?

00:27:24.800 --> 00:27:29.680
[Amit Varma]: And also one insight, as you point out in your book, and we can talk about that later,

00:27:29.680 --> 00:27:34.480
[Amit Varma]: is that even for those who don't believe in anything called natural rights, that rights

00:27:34.480 --> 00:27:40.000
[Amit Varma]: cannot be natural, it would still benefit all of us the most if we proceeded on the

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:44.160
[Amit Varma]: assumption that we begin with the right to self-ownership, which is at the heart of Locke's

00:27:44.160 --> 00:27:44.560
[Amit Varma]: thinking.

00:27:45.760 --> 00:27:46.720
[Guest]: Yes, well, that's right.

00:27:46.720 --> 00:27:53.120
[Guest]: So philosophers have been arguing ever since Locke about what rights are and whether they

00:27:53.120 --> 00:27:55.040
[Guest]: can actually be justified.

00:27:56.880 --> 00:28:04.240
[Guest]: But Locke's argument was that we have rights inherent in the nature of man as a being capable

00:28:04.240 --> 00:28:05.360
[Guest]: of reason.

00:28:05.360 --> 00:28:07.760
[Guest]: And so these rights are natural.

00:28:07.760 --> 00:28:13.360
[Guest]: We often say in the United States, the Constitution gives me the right to do that.

00:28:13.360 --> 00:28:17.520
[Guest]: Well, no, we really should say the Constitution protects my right to do that.

00:28:17.520 --> 00:28:23.440
[Guest]: I have a right to think the way I want to, to marry who I want to, to travel where I

00:28:23.440 --> 00:28:23.920
[Guest]: want to.

00:28:24.480 --> 00:28:28.160
[Guest]: The Constitution protects those rights.

00:28:28.160 --> 00:28:36.000
[Guest]: And so the rights are natural or unalienable, as we said in the Declaration of Independence.

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:43.280
[Guest]: And once we understand that, then we see the need for an agency to protect those rights

00:28:43.280 --> 00:28:45.040
[Guest]: from threats from other people.

00:28:45.600 --> 00:28:45.840
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:28:45.840 --> 00:28:51.520
[Amit Varma]: And what's happened in sort of modern times is that like all these terms get muddied,

00:28:51.520 --> 00:28:56.480
[Amit Varma]: the term rights has also gotten muddied in the sense that we have what I would rather

00:28:56.480 --> 00:29:01.840
[Amit Varma]: call entitlements, which aren't rights at all, also being spoken of as rights, for example,

00:29:01.840 --> 00:29:05.040
[Amit Varma]: the right to food, the right to livelihood, the right to broadband.

00:29:05.040 --> 00:29:07.840
[Amit Varma]: And so on, which are really positive rights.

00:29:07.840 --> 00:29:11.440
[Amit Varma]: Can you just sort of explain the difference between negative rights and positive rights

00:29:11.440 --> 00:29:14.080
[Amit Varma]: and how they muddy these waters?

00:29:15.040 --> 00:29:15.280
[Guest]: Yes.

00:29:16.160 --> 00:29:22.240
[Guest]: Negative rights means that I have a right to take action, to live as I choose without

00:29:22.240 --> 00:29:23.600
[Guest]: interference by others.

00:29:24.480 --> 00:29:31.120
[Guest]: So in that sense, you know, it is a negative on your ability to coerce me.

00:29:31.120 --> 00:29:38.560
[Guest]: Positive right means that I have a right to be given something by some agency, from you,

00:29:38.560 --> 00:29:42.480
[Guest]: from the government, from some human source.

00:29:43.040 --> 00:29:50.240
[Guest]: And the important point, I think, is that negative rights can be enjoyed by everyone

00:29:50.240 --> 00:29:54.160
[Guest]: in every society, no matter how poor the society is.

00:29:54.160 --> 00:29:58.960
[Guest]: We can all agree that we will not hit each other or take each other's stuff.

00:29:58.960 --> 00:30:04.160
[Guest]: We can agree that people can say whatever they want to and they will not be arrested

00:30:04.160 --> 00:30:05.760
[Guest]: or executed for it.

00:30:06.480 --> 00:30:11.040
[Guest]: We can agree that people can grow food on their own property and they can either eat

00:30:11.040 --> 00:30:13.520
[Guest]: it or exchange it with other people.

00:30:13.520 --> 00:30:19.280
[Guest]: When you start talking about positive rights, like the right to food or shelter, the right

00:30:19.280 --> 00:30:23.840
[Guest]: to a college education, the right to have your children taken care of at government

00:30:23.840 --> 00:30:32.240
[Guest]: expense, all of those things require someone else to provide this benefit to you.

00:30:32.800 --> 00:30:39.440
[Guest]: And because of that, they require infringing on your negative rights.

00:30:39.440 --> 00:30:46.880
[Guest]: When somebody says, I have a right to 12 years of education at public expense, which

00:30:46.880 --> 00:30:55.440
[Guest]: is what they always mean, then that means they have the power to tax me to educate their

00:30:55.440 --> 00:30:57.280
[Guest]: children for 12 years.

00:30:57.280 --> 00:31:00.080
[Guest]: Now, the argument is, well, it's all for all.

00:31:00.080 --> 00:31:01.600
[Guest]: We're all in this together.

00:31:01.600 --> 00:31:07.520
[Guest]: But of course, we all have different views about what kind of education is appropriate,

00:31:07.520 --> 00:31:10.800
[Guest]: what kind of health care, how we want to spend our money.

00:31:11.680 --> 00:31:16.240
[Guest]: When you tax me, you don't know exactly what cost you might be imposing on me.

00:31:16.240 --> 00:31:22.560
[Guest]: So negative rights can be enjoyed by everyone without infringing on other people.

00:31:22.560 --> 00:31:26.960
[Guest]: Positive rights can only be enjoyed at the expense of other people.

00:31:26.960 --> 00:31:33.200
[Guest]: And so one obvious point about positive rights is if you have a poor society, you simply

00:31:33.200 --> 00:31:35.360
[Guest]: can't have all these positive rights.

00:31:35.360 --> 00:31:40.000
[Guest]: And therefore, as an amateur philosopher, I would say, well, then they're not right.

00:31:40.720 --> 00:31:42.480
[Guest]: They may be entitlements.

00:31:42.480 --> 00:31:46.240
[Guest]: They may be things you think are a good idea when we get wealthy.

00:31:46.240 --> 00:31:52.480
[Guest]: But if you had tried to guarantee a right to food or a right to six years of education

00:31:53.200 --> 00:31:57.200
[Guest]: in the United States very early on, we just didn't have the money.

00:31:57.840 --> 00:32:01.520
[Guest]: India 50 years ago didn't have the money to do those things.

00:32:02.320 --> 00:32:07.200
[Guest]: Even today, the United States may not have the money to provide all the things that Bernie

00:32:07.200 --> 00:32:10.240
[Guest]: Sanders and other Democratic socialists want.

00:32:10.240 --> 00:32:14.960
[Guest]: And of course, when you try to supply all those things by government, you usually get

00:32:15.520 --> 00:32:23.360
[Guest]: less economic growth, therefore lower wages, less efficient economies, less useful services

00:32:23.360 --> 00:32:26.400
[Guest]: being provided, and sometimes much worse than that.

00:32:27.040 --> 00:32:28.960
[Amit Varma]: And I should really clarify on both our behalves.

00:32:28.960 --> 00:32:32.560
[Amit Varma]: Like when I talk about the difference between negative and positive rights, you know, especially

00:32:32.560 --> 00:32:36.480
[Amit Varma]: in India, people look at me and ask, how can you say, you know, there's no right to food

00:32:36.480 --> 00:32:38.240
[Amit Varma]: or water and these are just basic things.

00:32:38.240 --> 00:32:43.440
[Amit Varma]: And I'd like to point out that these are very desirable to say that they are not rights

00:32:43.440 --> 00:32:48.080
[Amit Varma]: is not to say that people should go hungry, or people should not be educated.

00:32:48.080 --> 00:32:53.120
[Amit Varma]: It's just to point out that if you want the state to provide for that, it comes at a cost,

00:32:53.120 --> 00:32:56.320
[Amit Varma]: it comes at a moral cost, obviously, of the violence that they're inflicting on other

00:32:56.320 --> 00:32:57.200
[Amit Varma]: citizens.

00:32:57.200 --> 00:33:02.480
[Amit Varma]: And it also comes at a cost to recipients themselves, because there's always a trade

00:33:02.480 --> 00:33:04.880
[Amit Varma]: off between this kind of distribution and growth.

00:33:04.880 --> 00:33:08.320
[Amit Varma]: And only growth lifts people out of poverty.

00:33:08.320 --> 00:33:14.720
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, there are better ways to achieve all of these things without necessarily using

00:33:14.720 --> 00:33:16.640
[Amit Varma]: coercive means.

00:33:16.640 --> 00:33:22.480
[Amit Varma]: And this, you know, often kind of gets lost in translation while talking about rights.

00:33:22.480 --> 00:33:27.360
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, obviously, for a poor country, there are difficult questions that this brings

00:33:27.360 --> 00:33:27.520
[Amit Varma]: up.

00:33:27.520 --> 00:33:31.360
[Amit Varma]: And I'll come to them a little later on, because I have a bunch of difficult questions

00:33:31.360 --> 00:33:36.000
[Amit Varma]: that libertarians should confront and answer.

00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:40.240
[Amit Varma]: So kind of, you know, again, moving on from Locke to, you know, the right to self ownership,

00:33:40.240 --> 00:33:45.680
[Amit Varma]: where his heart of the heart of his argument is that, look, you know, who owns us, you

00:33:45.680 --> 00:33:49.760
[Amit Varma]: know, it cannot be that everybody owns everybody that doesn't work, it cannot be that some

00:33:50.320 --> 00:33:52.880
[Amit Varma]: tyrant owns you, because, you know, where does that come from?

00:33:53.520 --> 00:33:58.880
[Amit Varma]: So it is natural and almost self evident to say that we own ourselves and that self ownership.

00:33:58.880 --> 00:34:02.880
[Amit Varma]: And from that, you get the right to life and liberty, you get the right to free speech.

00:34:02.880 --> 00:34:06.960
[Amit Varma]: And interestingly, and what I want to ask you about is the right to property.

00:34:06.960 --> 00:34:14.080
[Amit Varma]: Now, this is the right to property is something that is under dispute from essentially all

00:34:14.080 --> 00:34:19.040
[Amit Varma]: of these other philosophies of thinking, whether it's socialism or fascism or economic nationalism

00:34:19.040 --> 00:34:24.640
[Amit Varma]: or whatever, all of them, in some senses, attack the right to property and behave almost

00:34:24.640 --> 00:34:27.360
[Amit Varma]: as if there is something fundamentally immoral about this.

00:34:27.360 --> 00:34:28.720
[Amit Varma]: Can you unpack that for me?

00:34:29.600 --> 00:34:31.120
[Guest]: Yes, they all do.

00:34:31.120 --> 00:34:36.320
[Guest]: On the other hand, the right to property, the feeling that this thing I have worked

00:34:36.320 --> 00:34:41.840
[Guest]: for or this thing I have created is mine, I think is pretty natural to human beings.

00:34:42.880 --> 00:34:44.400
[Guest]: I don't think it's just in America.

00:34:44.400 --> 00:34:50.720
[Guest]: I think everywhere in the world, people feel that something I've created or land that

00:34:50.720 --> 00:34:51.680
[Guest]: I've worked.

00:34:51.680 --> 00:34:58.000
[Guest]: And that's what Locke said was that by mixing your labor with land that was formerly unowned,

00:34:58.000 --> 00:34:59.440
[Guest]: you make it yours.

00:34:59.440 --> 00:35:06.560
[Guest]: Now, a whole body of property law arises from that so that people now own land that they

00:35:06.560 --> 00:35:08.000
[Guest]: themselves have not worked.

00:35:08.000 --> 00:35:10.560
[Guest]: They may be renting it out to other people and so on.

00:35:10.560 --> 00:35:18.000
[Guest]: But it's come through a process of, at least in theory, originally, somebody mixed his

00:35:18.000 --> 00:35:23.760
[Guest]: labor with the land and acquired it that way and then was able, through a series of contracts,

00:35:23.760 --> 00:35:29.360
[Guest]: to transfer it to his children, to people to whom he sold it or rented it and so on.

00:35:30.720 --> 00:35:35.680
[Guest]: Societies that have actually tried to abolish the right of property have turned into disasters.

00:35:35.680 --> 00:35:40.720
[Guest]: The best example would be the Soviet Union after the 1917 Revolution.

00:35:40.720 --> 00:35:42.960
[Guest]: They were really dedicated communists.

00:35:42.960 --> 00:35:48.880
[Guest]: They really did believe from each according to his ability to each according to his needs,

00:35:48.880 --> 00:35:51.200
[Guest]: abolish property, abolish money.

00:35:51.200 --> 00:35:54.240
[Guest]: And it was an immediate disaster.

00:35:54.240 --> 00:35:57.760
[Guest]: We look at the pictures of Venezuela and we think how horrible that is.

00:35:57.760 --> 00:36:05.760
[Guest]: That sort of collapse happened in very short order in the Soviet Union from 1917 to 1921.

00:36:06.320 --> 00:36:11.520
[Guest]: And historians now call it war communism to blame it on the war.

00:36:11.520 --> 00:36:18.400
[Guest]: But what it was, was the best attempt ever to actually implement communism, a system

00:36:18.400 --> 00:36:27.520
[Guest]: of true public ownership of all the property in society and distribution of resources on

00:36:27.520 --> 00:36:30.880
[Guest]: the basis of need and not on the basis of money.

00:36:30.880 --> 00:36:35.520
[Guest]: And it was such a disaster that Lenin created the new economic policy, which essentially

00:36:35.520 --> 00:36:42.400
[Guest]: created a sort of extremely stunted and interventionist market economy.

00:36:42.400 --> 00:36:49.440
[Guest]: Because if you don't say this house is yours, this factory belongs, this factory is under

00:36:49.440 --> 00:36:55.360
[Guest]: the authority of someone who can make decisions about it, then you get total collapse of the

00:36:55.360 --> 00:36:58.800
[Guest]: economy the way they did in 1920, 21.

00:36:58.800 --> 00:37:08.320
[Guest]: So there are a lot of ideologies that do not believe in an absolute right to poverty.

00:37:09.040 --> 00:37:16.080
[Guest]: Most of them don't deny the efficacy of private property ownership.

00:37:16.080 --> 00:37:23.360
[Guest]: They just don't think it can be that it should be absolute because there are higher causes,

00:37:23.360 --> 00:37:30.000
[Guest]: whether that is allocating resources to our ethnic or religious group or indeed allocating

00:37:30.000 --> 00:37:35.680
[Guest]: resources simply to the needs of the nobles or the monarchs or the parliament or the ruling

00:37:35.680 --> 00:37:36.180
[Guest]: class.

00:37:37.680 --> 00:37:39.840
[Guest]: We have to make those kinds of exceptions.

00:37:41.120 --> 00:37:46.240
[Guest]: The countries that have been most successful have been those that have been best at protecting

00:37:46.240 --> 00:37:55.440
[Guest]: property rights of each individual, of each corporate entity, and not severely interfering

00:37:55.440 --> 00:37:57.680
[Guest]: with them through government interactions.

00:37:58.480 --> 00:38:04.640
[Amit Varma]: And of course, as you point out in your book, this is not just taking on from sort of a

00:38:04.640 --> 00:38:09.280
[Amit Varma]: logical continuation of the right to self-ownership and therefore almost a normative moral point

00:38:09.280 --> 00:38:10.160
[Amit Varma]: as it were.

00:38:10.160 --> 00:38:13.840
[Amit Varma]: But it's also for practical reasons that you need the right to property.

00:38:13.840 --> 00:38:18.240
[Amit Varma]: As you say in your book, quote, if our world were not characterized by scarcity, we wouldn't

00:38:18.240 --> 00:38:19.360
[Amit Varma]: need property rights.

00:38:20.480 --> 00:38:21.120
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:38:21.120 --> 00:38:26.160
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, I had an episode on the right to property about how it's been eroded in

00:38:26.160 --> 00:38:29.520
[Amit Varma]: India, like it started off as one of our fundamental rights and now it no longer is.

00:38:29.520 --> 00:38:33.920
[Amit Varma]: I had an episode on that with the economist Shruti Rajagopalan where she elaborated on

00:38:33.920 --> 00:38:35.200
[Amit Varma]: this much more.

00:38:35.200 --> 00:38:40.720
[Amit Varma]: But another thing that, you know, not having a strong right to property does is it affects

00:38:40.720 --> 00:38:41.360
[Amit Varma]: incentives.

00:38:41.360 --> 00:38:44.880
[Amit Varma]: And I'll just tell you a quick story about something that a friend of mine worked on.

00:38:44.880 --> 00:38:50.320
[Amit Varma]: There's a friend of mine called Barun Mitra, a writer in Delhi, who campaigned for many

00:38:50.320 --> 00:38:55.760
[Amit Varma]: years to get a group of tribals property rights on land that they'd been occupying for generations.

00:38:56.320 --> 00:39:00.320
[Amit Varma]: I think it was in the state of Gujarat with other activists.

00:39:00.320 --> 00:39:06.320
[Amit Varma]: And finally, it came through and very innovatively using technology, using GPS data over a period

00:39:06.320 --> 00:39:10.480
[Amit Varma]: of years, they managed to prove that this land was indeed theirs and they got the land

00:39:10.480 --> 00:39:15.840
[Amit Varma]: rights. And the first thing they did when they got legal title was they built toilets

00:39:15.840 --> 00:39:16.480
[Amit Varma]: in their houses.

00:39:17.360 --> 00:39:23.840
[Amit Varma]: And that to me is just so revelatory of the power of the incentive of property rights

00:39:23.840 --> 00:39:28.880
[Amit Varma]: that the moment people actually own property, you have private ownership, the incentives

00:39:28.880 --> 00:39:32.480
[Amit Varma]: change, they look after that property so much better.

00:39:32.480 --> 00:39:37.360
[Amit Varma]: And you can just see the difference between private and public property pretty much everywhere.

00:39:38.400 --> 00:39:39.840
[Guest]: Yes, you absolutely can.

00:39:39.840 --> 00:39:43.680
[Guest]: You know, there's a saying in the United States, nobody ever washes a rented car.

00:39:45.120 --> 00:39:46.480
[Guest]: You wash your own car.

00:39:46.480 --> 00:39:50.240
[Guest]: You want to keep up the value of your car, but you don't have much incentive to wash

00:39:50.240 --> 00:39:52.640
[Guest]: a car you're just renting for a few days.

00:39:53.280 --> 00:39:55.440
[Guest]: That's that's the problem of the owner.

00:39:55.440 --> 00:40:00.000
[Guest]: And the same thing is true with publicly owned housing.

00:40:00.000 --> 00:40:06.240
[Guest]: It tends to deteriorate because there's no owner there who cares that when a window is

00:40:06.240 --> 00:40:10.800
[Guest]: broken or a window sill is cracked, that you need to fix that.

00:40:10.800 --> 00:40:14.240
[Guest]: And it's true even just with renters of housing.

00:40:14.240 --> 00:40:20.240
[Guest]: If I'm renting an apartment, I care how good it is to live in, but its long term value

00:40:20.240 --> 00:40:22.000
[Guest]: is of less interest to me.

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:28.320
[Guest]: So keeping up the maintenance, painting when appropriate, patching holes, all those things

00:40:28.320 --> 00:40:32.240
[Guest]: I'm going to be less careful about than I would be if I owned it.

00:40:32.240 --> 00:40:37.840
[Guest]: And of course, people who are renting out their property develop ways to take care of

00:40:37.840 --> 00:40:38.080
[Guest]: that.

00:40:38.080 --> 00:40:39.680
[Guest]: They have security deposits.

00:40:39.680 --> 00:40:42.240
[Guest]: They have they check in sometimes.

00:40:42.240 --> 00:40:46.800
[Guest]: They make sure the the renter knows that you can call me if there's a problem because I

00:40:46.800 --> 00:40:49.520
[Guest]: will want to fix it, all that sort of thing.

00:40:49.520 --> 00:40:54.800
[Guest]: But it's absolutely true that if you take away the ownership incentive, people have

00:40:54.800 --> 00:41:02.880
[Guest]: much less reason to make their property well maintained, long lasting and productive.

00:41:02.880 --> 00:41:10.480
[Guest]: The fact that I am able to reap the benefits of whatever I plant on my property makes me

00:41:10.480 --> 00:41:11.440
[Guest]: want to do that.

00:41:11.440 --> 00:41:18.000
[Guest]: If I am allowed to plant corn on a piece of land, but I don't actually own the land, then

00:41:18.000 --> 00:41:20.480
[Guest]: I'm not going to build a house for myself.

00:41:20.480 --> 00:41:26.000
[Guest]: I will build a house when I know that I have secure property rights or secure rental rights.

00:41:26.000 --> 00:41:30.160
[Guest]: If I'm confident that I live in a society with the rule of law and I've rented this

00:41:30.160 --> 00:41:33.840
[Guest]: property for 20 years, then maybe I build a house.

00:41:36.160 --> 00:41:40.320
[Guest]: Property rights create the incentive to maintain property.

00:41:40.320 --> 00:41:44.320
[Guest]: And one of the points there, you know, from a sort of environmentalist or sustainable

00:41:44.320 --> 00:41:51.760
[Guest]: development point, is it's ownership that makes people look at the long term.

00:41:51.760 --> 00:41:57.200
[Guest]: Because I figure someday I'm going to sell this property or maybe I'm going to leave

00:41:57.200 --> 00:41:58.480
[Guest]: it to my son or daughter.

00:41:59.120 --> 00:42:06.240
[Guest]: But either way, I have a long term interest in maintaining the quality of the property,

00:42:06.240 --> 00:42:09.760
[Guest]: whether that's a house or a field or a forest or whatever.

00:42:09.760 --> 00:42:15.840
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, moving on from sort of the moral case for libertarianism, for respecting

00:42:15.840 --> 00:42:19.440
[Amit Varma]: individual freedom, which is that which comes from self ownership, we all own ourselves

00:42:19.440 --> 00:42:21.520
[Amit Varma]: for the right to life and liberty and all of that.

00:42:22.320 --> 00:42:27.200
[Amit Varma]: There's also a consequentialist case which simply argues that, listen, forget natural

00:42:27.200 --> 00:42:28.480
[Amit Varma]: rights, it doesn't matter.

00:42:28.480 --> 00:42:33.680
[Amit Varma]: If you want society to grow and to prosper, then you need individual freedom.

00:42:33.680 --> 00:42:35.280
[Amit Varma]: Expand on that a little bit.

00:42:35.280 --> 00:42:40.320
[Amit Varma]: What evidence we have to show that freedom really benefits the world at large?

00:42:40.320 --> 00:42:41.040
[Guest]: Well, that's right.

00:42:41.040 --> 00:42:47.040
[Guest]: So my own view is basically I agree with the Declaration of Independence.

00:42:47.040 --> 00:42:52.240
[Guest]: All men are endowed by their creator or by nature with certain inalienable rights.

00:42:52.240 --> 00:42:54.480
[Guest]: And that is a self evident truth.

00:42:55.120 --> 00:43:01.920
[Guest]: I believe that it is wrong to use force against other people, except defensively.

00:43:01.920 --> 00:43:05.920
[Guest]: So if you're pointing a gun at me, I have a right to defend myself.

00:43:05.920 --> 00:43:11.920
[Guest]: But otherwise, I should not be the one to pick up a stick or a gun and try to take something

00:43:11.920 --> 00:43:14.240
[Guest]: of yours or impose my will on you.

00:43:14.240 --> 00:43:16.800
[Guest]: And to me, that is self evident.

00:43:16.800 --> 00:43:22.800
[Guest]: And I think to most people, even if they can't develop a theory of individual rights, they

00:43:22.800 --> 00:43:28.480
[Guest]: know it's wrong to pick up a gun or a stick and force people to act in a way they wouldn't

00:43:28.480 --> 00:43:28.960
[Guest]: want to.

00:43:28.960 --> 00:43:34.000
[Guest]: So that is the self evident case for individual rights.

00:43:34.000 --> 00:43:36.000
[Guest]: But it is also true.

00:43:36.880 --> 00:43:38.880
[Guest]: And, you know, I work at a policy institute.

00:43:38.880 --> 00:43:42.480
[Guest]: So what we make are consequentialist arguments all the time.

00:43:43.440 --> 00:43:49.760
[Guest]: Set aside whether it is, in fact, a whether we are endowed by our creator with certain

00:43:49.760 --> 00:43:51.040
[Guest]: inalienable rights.

00:43:51.040 --> 00:43:59.360
[Guest]: Let's just say we want to live in a society that is peaceful and prosperous and harmonious.

00:43:59.360 --> 00:44:01.040
[Guest]: How do we make that happen?

00:44:01.040 --> 00:44:07.440
[Guest]: Well, it seems clear we do need to respect people's individual choices, whether or not

00:44:07.440 --> 00:44:08.400
[Guest]: you think it's a right.

00:44:08.960 --> 00:44:15.760
[Guest]: Respecting people's choices allows them to advance their own interests in a way that

00:44:15.760 --> 00:44:18.080
[Guest]: doesn't harm other people.

00:44:18.080 --> 00:44:23.520
[Guest]: Allowing private property means that people have an incentive to use their property to

00:44:23.520 --> 00:44:24.800
[Guest]: create wealth.

00:44:24.800 --> 00:44:31.200
[Guest]: Allowing market exchanges means that people have an incentive to think of how they can

00:44:31.200 --> 00:44:32.240
[Guest]: serve others.

00:44:32.240 --> 00:44:38.720
[Guest]: You know, we we do talk about libertarianism in terms of individualism and individual rights.

00:44:38.720 --> 00:44:44.560
[Guest]: But really, it's a system that enables cooperation.

00:44:44.560 --> 00:44:51.920
[Guest]: And we libertarians believe in cooperation so strongly that we want social institutions

00:44:51.920 --> 00:44:55.920
[Guest]: that enable it and social institutions like private property.

00:44:55.920 --> 00:44:57.120
[Guest]: I know what is mine.

00:44:57.120 --> 00:44:58.720
[Guest]: I know what is yours.

00:44:58.720 --> 00:44:59.920
[Guest]: Market exchange.

00:44:59.920 --> 00:45:03.120
[Guest]: I can exchange some of what I have for some of what you have.

00:45:04.160 --> 00:45:06.880
[Guest]: The rule of law, sound money.

00:45:06.880 --> 00:45:12.720
[Guest]: The fact that I know if I sell this to you for ten dollars, that ten dollars will be

00:45:12.720 --> 00:45:13.760
[Guest]: worth it.

00:45:13.760 --> 00:45:18.720
[Guest]: Ten dollars will be worth just as much a year from now, ten years from now.

00:45:18.720 --> 00:45:24.000
[Guest]: The sounder the money is, the easier it is to make economic transactions.

00:45:24.000 --> 00:45:34.320
[Guest]: So all the benefits that we see from economic growth rest on the idea that people own things,

00:45:34.320 --> 00:45:40.560
[Guest]: other people own other things, and we're all allowed to make exchanges and contracts with

00:45:40.560 --> 00:45:47.520
[Guest]: each other in order to achieve mutually beneficial improvements in our situation.

00:45:47.520 --> 00:45:53.920
[Guest]: And you take each one of those improvements and you add up hundreds of millions of those

00:45:53.920 --> 00:45:57.760
[Guest]: improvements and you get economic growth.

00:45:57.760 --> 00:46:03.280
[Guest]: You move from the quality of life in 1900 to the quality of life in 2000.

00:46:04.400 --> 00:46:04.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:46:04.560 --> 00:46:10.800
[Amit Varma]: You know, one of the things that's always baffled me is that it's fairly evident that

00:46:10.800 --> 00:46:14.960
[Amit Varma]: you know, all of political philosophy is really this tussle between liberty and power.

00:46:14.960 --> 00:46:19.600
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, you'd imagine the political spectrum to split up like that, where you

00:46:19.600 --> 00:46:24.160
[Amit Varma]: have extreme liberty, you have complete liberty on one side and, you know, statism and power

00:46:24.160 --> 00:46:24.720
[Amit Varma]: on the other side.

00:46:24.720 --> 00:46:26.400
[Amit Varma]: But that's not how it's split up.

00:46:26.400 --> 00:46:31.280
[Amit Varma]: For example, one of the things that baffles me is that, look, almost everybody will agree

00:46:31.280 --> 00:46:36.000
[Amit Varma]: that it is okay for two consenting adults to do whatever they want with each other as

00:46:36.000 --> 00:46:38.080
[Amit Varma]: long as they're not infringing someone else's rights.

00:46:38.720 --> 00:46:42.960
[Amit Varma]: But people will have different approaches to whether that happens in a bedroom or whether

00:46:42.960 --> 00:46:44.160
[Amit Varma]: it happens in the marketplace.

00:46:44.160 --> 00:46:49.600
[Amit Varma]: There'll be one group of people who will say that no, personal freedoms are sacrosanct,

00:46:49.600 --> 00:46:53.040
[Amit Varma]: but hey, when it comes to the marketplace, the principle suddenly changes and the state

00:46:53.040 --> 00:46:54.240
[Amit Varma]: must intervene.

00:46:54.240 --> 00:46:59.680
[Amit Varma]: And there'll be other groups of people who will kind of look at it differently and want

00:46:59.680 --> 00:47:04.240
[Amit Varma]: economic freedom in the marketplace, but they will want to clamp down on personal freedoms.

00:47:04.960 --> 00:47:10.480
[Amit Varma]: You know, and this dissonance is what causes people to say that, hey, I'm socially liberal

00:47:10.480 --> 00:47:13.360
[Amit Varma]: and fiscally conservative, you know, which kind of baffles me.

00:47:13.360 --> 00:47:15.760
[Amit Varma]: How has the spectrum divvied up like this?

00:47:17.200 --> 00:47:22.240
[Guest]: Well, one of the problems is that when you state libertarian principles in their broadest

00:47:22.240 --> 00:47:28.480
[Guest]: form, like everybody should have the right to live their life as they choose, make the

00:47:28.480 --> 00:47:31.840
[Guest]: decisions they want so long as they don't interfere with the rights of others.

00:47:31.840 --> 00:47:33.040
[Guest]: Everybody agrees with that.

00:47:33.040 --> 00:47:34.080
[Guest]: And then you're right.

00:47:34.080 --> 00:47:37.360
[Guest]: People have different views of, oh, but I didn't mean that.

00:47:37.360 --> 00:47:44.640
[Guest]: No, no, that's against God's will or that's not helping the poor, not helping the marginalized

00:47:44.640 --> 00:47:45.040
[Guest]: people.

00:47:46.480 --> 00:47:53.360
[Guest]: So they divide into different groups on the basis of which ways they want to violate individual

00:47:53.360 --> 00:47:56.800
[Guest]: rights, that they think that should override that.

00:47:56.800 --> 00:47:59.520
[Guest]: Why have they divided this particular way?

00:47:59.520 --> 00:48:00.800
[Guest]: That's an interesting question.

00:48:00.800 --> 00:48:04.800
[Guest]: I don't know that it's true all over the world, and it hasn't always been true.

00:48:04.800 --> 00:48:11.760
[Guest]: Obviously, there was a time when, at least in European history, you had the old regime

00:48:11.760 --> 00:48:15.760
[Guest]: of monarchy and nobility and the established church.

00:48:15.760 --> 00:48:22.240
[Guest]: And then you had liberalism, which argued for the rights of individuals and the rights

00:48:22.240 --> 00:48:26.640
[Guest]: of markets and contracts, right to make contracts.

00:48:26.640 --> 00:48:31.360
[Guest]: And so there you did have liberalism versus statism.

00:48:32.000 --> 00:48:41.840
[Guest]: One argument is that as liberalism got rolling, this new idea of socialism came into existence.

00:48:41.840 --> 00:48:49.360
[Guest]: And socialism wanted to achieve the goals of liberalism, widespread prosperity.

00:48:49.360 --> 00:48:55.440
[Guest]: But it did it with, in a sense, old-fashioned authoritarian methods, the kind of methods

00:48:55.440 --> 00:49:02.400
[Guest]: the kings and queens had used to take people's property, redistribute it, reassign it, forbid

00:49:02.400 --> 00:49:09.200
[Guest]: people to do things that violated some rule or somebody's idea of what should be a social

00:49:09.200 --> 00:49:09.520
[Guest]: norm.

00:49:09.520 --> 00:49:18.960
[Guest]: And as liberalism basically eradicated the old order so that in the Western world, we

00:49:18.960 --> 00:49:25.520
[Guest]: just don't have kings and queens with power anymore, the people who might otherwise have

00:49:25.520 --> 00:49:34.000
[Guest]: been defenders of the old order, the kings and the nobles, became conservatives who preferred

00:49:34.000 --> 00:49:40.080
[Guest]: the system of liberal markets to socialism.

00:49:40.080 --> 00:49:48.720
[Guest]: And so then you got a world where it was sort of market liberalism against socialism, which

00:49:48.720 --> 00:49:55.200
[Guest]: still claimed to support liberal values of individual rights and seeking prosperity.

00:49:55.200 --> 00:50:01.520
[Guest]: And people who were more moderate socialists then continued to believe mostly in freedom

00:50:01.520 --> 00:50:06.480
[Guest]: of speech and rights for minorities and those kinds of things.

00:50:06.480 --> 00:50:11.760
[Guest]: But they didn't believe very strongly in rights of private property and free enterprise.

00:50:11.760 --> 00:50:16.240
[Guest]: So I think at least in England and the United States and maybe the rest of Europe, that's

00:50:16.240 --> 00:50:18.800
[Guest]: part of the division that was happening.

00:50:19.920 --> 00:50:27.520
[Guest]: I've heard people say that one of the reasons for the differences you're talking about is

00:50:27.520 --> 00:50:36.160
[Guest]: that people want to regulate or outlaw the impulses that they fear in themselves.

00:50:36.160 --> 00:50:44.400
[Guest]: And that if people are perhaps particularly drawn to sexual activities that they fear

00:50:44.400 --> 00:50:51.600
[Guest]: may actually be wrong, or they're drawn to look at pornography or to use mind-altering

00:50:51.600 --> 00:50:57.680
[Guest]: substances like alcohol or marijuana, that's what they want to outlaw.

00:50:57.680 --> 00:51:01.200
[Guest]: So they want to outlaw homosexuality or adultery.

00:51:01.200 --> 00:51:03.280
[Guest]: They want to outlaw marijuana.

00:51:03.280 --> 00:51:05.600
[Guest]: Sometimes they want to outlaw alcohol.

00:51:05.600 --> 00:51:15.200
[Guest]: And alternatively, if what you fear in yourself is greed and you fear that you just know that

00:51:15.200 --> 00:51:21.200
[Guest]: if you had the opportunity, you would cheat people, then you want a big government structure

00:51:21.200 --> 00:51:25.040
[Guest]: to prevent people from being greedy and cheating others.

00:51:25.920 --> 00:51:33.040
[Guest]: I've also heard the theory that actually a friend of mine made that argument once.

00:51:33.040 --> 00:51:35.920
[Guest]: And I said, so then what do libertarians fear?

00:51:35.920 --> 00:51:38.080
[Guest]: And he said, they fear the will to power.

00:51:38.080 --> 00:51:41.680
[Guest]: They feel in themselves a will to power.

00:51:41.680 --> 00:51:45.440
[Guest]: They know it's wrong, and therefore they want to control power.

00:51:45.440 --> 00:51:45.920
[Guest]: I don't know.

00:51:45.920 --> 00:51:48.080
[Guest]: I don't feel like I feel a will to power.

00:51:48.080 --> 00:51:50.720
[Guest]: But there could be something to that.

00:51:50.720 --> 00:51:56.320
[Guest]: At any rate, there are many arguments for infringing on other people's liberty.

00:51:57.280 --> 00:52:03.600
[Guest]: They usually go back to something that you personally find morally offensive, whether

00:52:03.600 --> 00:52:08.080
[Guest]: it's smoking marijuana or paying someone less than the minimum wage.

00:52:09.680 --> 00:52:14.320
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and I certainly don't feel the will to power either, though I do feel a will to

00:52:14.320 --> 00:52:16.240
[Amit Varma]: be just left alone.

00:52:16.240 --> 00:52:21.040
[Amit Varma]: There's a great quote by you in your book again, which really sums it up really nicely.

00:52:21.040 --> 00:52:25.200
[Amit Varma]: And I like quoting this to people, which is quote, conservatives want to be your daddy

00:52:25.200 --> 00:52:27.520
[Amit Varma]: telling you what to do and what not to do.

00:52:27.520 --> 00:52:31.520
[Amit Varma]: Liberals want to be your mommy feeding you, tucking you in and wiping your nose.

00:52:31.520 --> 00:52:34.080
[Amit Varma]: Libertarians want to treat you as an adult.

00:52:34.720 --> 00:52:35.360
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:52:35.360 --> 00:52:39.280
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, I think the problem, at least sitting where I am in India, where, of course,

00:52:39.280 --> 00:52:42.240
[Amit Varma]: I am probably one of about three or four libertarians in the whole country.

00:52:42.240 --> 00:52:49.200
[Amit Varma]: But the problem here is that both sides of our political spectrum, such as it is, want

00:52:49.200 --> 00:52:52.400
[Amit Varma]: to be both your daddy and your mommy to differing extents.

00:52:52.400 --> 00:52:56.800
[Amit Varma]: There's just no respect for individual freedom or rights or even what it entails.

00:52:56.800 --> 00:52:58.080
[Amit Varma]: It's not even part of the discourse.

